Borges said that being a reader is always more noble than being an author, because an author can never say everything right, will always make mistakes, express himself only partially, etc. But a reader always reads perfectly. He can do no mistakes in his act of mere pure reading.

I think this applies to politics and geopolitical shows like the one. No one is obligated to make predictions. I refuse to make any because inevitably they will be wrong. We have the human right to just lean back and see what happens, without guessing blind, if we only desire so.
In the end, you never know what life will serve you.

Few weeks ago I was reading a bit about prairie dog language and was struck that it sounded a little similar to some constructions in The Iliad like "white-armed Hera". Like it seems they say "blue-shirted man approaching". I don't speak either Greek or prairie doggish though tbh

I can't really elaborate on it further due to an extreme lack of knowledge on the topic, but it just seems to me that a lot of Homeric phrases would translate really well into prairie dog language and a lot of prairie dog sentences would not sound too out of place in Antiquity.
I take solace in the fact that I am the first and probably last man ever to notice this
